<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3>Should I age Cabernet Sauvignon or drink it young?</h3>
    <p>Most Cabernet Sauvignon under $30 drinks best within 2-5 years of vintage. Premium bottles ($50+) from quality producers can improve for 10-20 years with proper storage. Taste young to understand the wine's trajectory.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3>What's the difference between Napa and Washington State Cabernet Sauvignon?</h3>
    <p>Napa Valley typically produces richer, more powerful wines with higher alcohol and price points. Washington State creates more food-friendly wines with bright acidity and excellent value across all price ranges.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3>How much should I spend on good Cabernet Sauvignon?</h3>
    <p>$25-40 provides excellent quality for regular drinking. $50-100 enters premium territory with aging potential. Above $100 targets collectors and special occasions. Start lower and work up as your palate develops.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3>Can beginners enjoy Cabernet Sauvignon?</h3>
    <p>Yes, but start with fruit-forward styles from warmer climates and moderate tannin levels. Washington State and Australian bottles often show more approachable profiles than Napa Valley or Bordeaux wines.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3>What foods complement Cabernet Sauvignon best?</h3>
    <p>Red meat, aged cheeses, and grilled vegetables work excellently. The wine's tannins cut through rich, fatty foods while complementing protein flavors. Avoid delicate fish or light poultry dishes.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3>How do I know if a vintage is worth buying?</h3>
    <p>Research vintage charts for your target region. Great vintages command higher prices but offer superior quality and aging potential. Average vintages can provide excellent value if priced appropriately.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3>Should I buy Cabernet Sauvignon blends or 100% varietal wines?</h3>
    <p>Both offer advantages. 100% Cabernet Sauvignon shows pure varietal character, while blends (especially Bordeaux-style) provide complexity and food compatibility. Try both styles to determine your preference.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3>What's the biggest mistake when buying expensive Cabernet Sauvignon?</h3>
    <p>Purchasing without understanding your storage capacity and drinking timeline. Expensive bottles require proper cellaring conditions and patience. Also avoid buying based solely on scores without considering personal taste preferences.</p>
